EScript is a dynamic language.

In most compiled languages like C/++, variables can only have one type which must be determinable at compile time.
Say, int x;
x = "im evil"; // Produces a compiler error
x = 1.2; // Silently truncates to 1

In EScript, akin to Python, variables are just labels on containers.
Say our container (where we put our "data" in) is an integer, or a list, it doesn't matter. We label it "x".
This is all our variable really is.

Variables however, must be assigned valid values only. Variables can not have an indeterminate value
at any point. For example:
let y = x^2
where x hasn't been declared yet. We ~may~ expect our language to form an equation, y = x^2, and plug
in the value of x when it gets it. But that isn't how it works.
Our variable can have ~any~ value! An integer, a float, list, string, map, even custom structures! It just needs to have
some concrete value.

Variables in EScript, as you have seen in the above example, can be declared using the 'let' prefix.
When variables are declared without an initializer, they are given the value 'null'. See 'BuiltinTypes' for info on what null is.
A variable's name must not start with an integer (though it can start with any other *valid* character, even underscore).
The name ("identifier") must only include alphabets(a-zA-Z) or integers(0-9) and the humber underscore.

let x; => valid
let xy; => valid
let lakjsdlfkjaklsdjflkjalkjdfkljalsdlfklkj; => valid
let 123abc; => NOT valid
let C.Users.Hackler; => NOT valid (only a-Z,0-9 and _ are allowed!)
let abc123; => valid
let _gaming; => valid (Remember, only integers at the start aren't valid)
let _; => valid (Did we ever say this wasn't valid?)

Now you may ask about the seemingly arbitrary restriction that variable names can not start with numbers.
This is more or less a historical artifact from old languages like C. Compilers back then couldn't read ahead to determine if 123abc
was a complete variable name or an integer literal. Memory was a very big constraint back then. It couldn't just read in the whole string
and decide. Also, not allowing this let the compiler just know that if a "token" starts with an integer, then it can only be an integer.
No ambiguity. Less complexity. Faster compilation. Yay :3

Two variables can not be declared in the same "scope" (you will learn later what that is) with the same name. This is will produce a compiler error.
However, a local variable decleration can overshadow a decleration from a higher scope. This is defined behaviour, though not recommended.
Overshadowing isn't recommended because it can complicate the execution flow for yourself.